<h2 id="_1_info_top_flop_customers">1. 1) Info: Top / Flop customers</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This statistic shows the revenue data sorted according to <strong>top customers</strong> (those are the customers who generated the most revenue during the selected <strong>time span</strong>) and <strong>flop customers</strong> (those are the customers who generated the least revenue). Default setting for the time span: <strong>the last 12 months</strong>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="_2_details_about_the_statistic">2. 2) Details about the statistic</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The number of sales orders and the revenue generated by each customer will be displayed for the selected <strong>time span</strong> and the sort of customer that you choose the statistic to be <strong>based on</strong>. Depending on your selection, you will either see the <strong>top customers</strong> - those are the customers who generated the <strong>most revenue</strong> or the <strong>flop customers</strong> - those are the customers who generated the <strong>least revenue</strong>. The customers will be listed in descending order. In other words, the list of tops will begin with the customer who generated the most <strong>revenue</strong>. This list will end with whichever top customer generated the least revenue. The list of flops is exactly the opposite. In other words, the list begins with whichever customer generated the least revenue and progresses with customers who generated more and more revenue. In this statistic you can see, e.g. which customers generated a very large or a very small amount of revenue. You could use this information, e.g. to set up special deals for individual customers.</p>
</div>
